Hello,

I was wondering if yang2dsdl can validate a leafref in one module referencing a leaf in a different module (not an augment).

First module is leafrefs.yang :+1: 

module leafrefs {
  yang-version  1;
  namespace "http://example.com/leafrefs";
  prefix "lr";
  organization "Example";
  contact
    "abc@example.com";
  description
    "Leafrefs";
  revision "2015-02-10" {
    description "Initial revision";
  }
  list l1 {
    key "name";
    leaf name {
      type string;
    }
  }
}

Second module is leafrefs2.yang : 

module leafrefs2 {
  yang-version  1;
  namespace "http://example.com/leafrefs2";
  prefix "l2";
  import leafrefs {
    prefix "l";
  }
  organization "Example";
  contact
    "abc@example.com";
  description
    "leafrefs2";
  revision "2015-02-10" {
    description "Initial revision";
  }
  list l2 {
    key "id";
    leaf id {
      type uint8;
    }
    leaf l1-ref {
      type leafref {
        path "/l:l1/l:name";
        require-instance true;
      }
    }
  }
}

Data to be verified:

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<data xmlns="urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:netconf:base:1.0">
  <l1 xmlns="http://example.com/leafrefs">
    <name>local</name>
  </l1>
  <l2 xmlns="http://example.com/leafrefs2">
    <id>1</id>
    <l1-ref>abc</l1-ref>
  </l2>
</data>


Thanks,
Helen

I want to finetune the ```dlib_face_recognition_resnet_model_v1.dat``` model using some new datasets. I think the first step to finetune this model is to **detect** faces in the training images and then **align** the detected faces, and at last  feed the aligned faces into the model as input. But in the ```dnn_face_recognition_ex.cpp``` files the author says the following differences, and not mention the **face detection** and **align**.
> // Also, the dnn_metric_learning_on_images_ex.cpp example shows how to train this network.
// The dlib_face_recognition_resnet_model_v1 model used by this example was trained using
// essentially the code shown in dnn_metric_learning_on_images_ex.cpp except the
// mini-batches were made larger (35x15 instead of 5x5), the iterations without progress
// was set to 10000, the jittering you can see below in jitter_image() was used during
// training, and the training dataset consisted of about 3 million images instead of 55. 

I just want to find out have you did the detection and alignment during you training process.

The motivation is setting different error message on SchemaError when trying to validate a single type.

This is the code:
```python
class Is(And):
    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        super(Is, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
        self._type = args[0]

    def validate(self, data):
        if not isinstance(data, self._type):
            error_message = '{} did not validate {}'.format(
                repr(self),
                repr(data)
            )
            raise SchemaError(error_message, error_message)
        return True
```

And usage:
```python
SCHEMA = Schema({
    'number': Is(int, error='Invalid zipcode param'),
})
```

Should I create a PR?

